section.t:
For now, possible Role values are: 
         Provider - speaker is a transit provider to neighbor;
         Customer - speaker is customer of neighbor;
         Peer     - speaker and neighbor are peers;
         Internal - speaker is part of an internal AS of an
         organization which has multiple ASs, is a confederation, ...

The TLV (type, length, value) of the BGP Role capability
    are: 
     Type   - <TBD1>;
     Length - 1 (octet);
     Value - integer corresponding to speaker' BGP Role.

If a speaker receives a BGP Role capability, it SHOULD check
    value of received capability with its own BGP Role. The allowed
    pairings are (first is its own Role, second is received
    Role): 
     (Peer, Peer);  
     (Provider, Customer); 
     (Customer, Provider); 
     (Internal, Internal); 
     In all other cases speaker MUST send a Role Mismatch
    Notification (code 2, sub-code <TBD2>).

There are four rules for usage of AVM attribute:
The AVM attribute SHOULD be added to all incoming routes if receiver's Role is Provider or Peer;
Routes with the AVM attribute set MUST NOT be announced if the speaker's Role is Provider or Peer;
The AVM attribute SHOULD be added to all outgoing routes if the speaker has not sent the Role capability in the OPEN message and speaker's Role is Customer or Peer;
If the receiver's Role is Customer or Peer, all incoming routes with the AVM attribute set SHOULD have low Local Preference Attribute or MAY be filtered.
The first two rules avoid creation of route leak inside an AS. The last two rules provide detection of route leaks made by some other AS in the AS_Path.
